    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so when the lactic acid is building up, does it feel like it's actually causing the burn? like what is physically happening in the tissue that makes it feel so uncomfortable while i'm working out?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The burning sensation during intense exercise is not solely due to lactic acid itself, though it's a major factor. Instead, the buildup of hydrogen ions ($\\text{H}^+$) associated with lactate production is what significantly lowers the pH in the muscle tissue, making it more acidic. This acidity interferes with the muscle fibers' ability to contract efficiently, which is what you perceive as that intense, uncomfortable burn. It's a metabolic signal telling your muscles they are working at maximum capacity.",
      "source": "target",
